JPA (Java Persistence API)

JPA (Java Persistence API) is a Java specification that defines a standard way to map Java objects to relational database
tables using Object-Relational Mapping (ORM). It provides interfaces, annotations (such as @Entity, @Id, and @Table), and
APIs like EntityManager to interact with the database. However, JPA itself does not contain any implementation code, so it
cannot perform database operations on its own. It requires a JPA provider, such as Hibernate, to execute the actual persistence operations.

Hibernate

Hibernate is an ORM framework and one of the most popular implementations of the JPA specification. It provides the actual implementation 
for all the interfaces defined by JPA and is responsible for converting Java objects into database records and vice versa. Hibernate 
automatically generates SQL queries, manages database connections, handles transactions, supports caching, and performs CRUD
(Create, Read, Update, Delete) operations. While Hibernate can be used directly through its own APIs (such as the Session interface), 
it is most commonly used as the JPA provider in Spring applications.

Spring Data JPA

Spring Data JPA is a Spring Framework module that simplifies working with JPA by reducing the amount of boilerplate code developers need
to write. It is built on top of JPA and uses a JPA implementation, typically Hibernate, to perform database operations. Instead of writing
DAO or repository implementation classes, developers simply create an interface that extends JpaRepository, and Spring Data JPA automatically 
provides implementations for common CRUD operations such as save(), findById(), findAll(), and deleteById(). It also supports automatic query
generation through method names, pagination, sorting, and custom queries, making database access faster and more efficient.
